    <description>The Wide Field Camera 3 (WFC3) aboard the Hubble Space Telescope is a camera that is meant to cover a very large field of view and a very large range of wavelengths. The UV/optical channel of WFC3 has a field of view of 164 arcseconds square and covers wavelengths from 200 to 1000 nm, while the infrared channel of WFC3 has a field of view of 135 by 127 arcseconds and covers wavelengths from 800 to 1700 nm. WFC3 was installed in 2009 and replaced the Wide Field Planetary Camera 2 (WFPC2).</description>
